<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06021158 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06021158 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  IRAQI-US; SUPPORT; WAR; DELAY; MEETING; LOS-ANGELES  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  In an attempt to speak out on behalf of Iraqi civilians under fire in thePersian Gulf war, a diverse coalition of Iraqi-Americans made an emotionalpublic appeal Sunday for a one-day cease-fire to allow the International RedCross to assess civilian casualties in their homeland.;    Americans have beenable to support the war because they have yet to see a single Iraqi civiliancasualty on television, said Raad Omar of Glendale, an Iraqi-born computerexpert who is a U.S. citizen.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  IRAQI-AMERICANS SEEK 1-DAY TRUCE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;We have seen injuries from a dozen Scud missiles in Israel. Imagine howmany injuries there must be from 7,000 bombs falling in Iraq,&quot; Omar said.&quot;Even if they have an 80 percent success rate, as the generals say, we mustask: Where did the other 20 percent of the bombs fall?&quot;;    Members of thecoalition, which includes a wide range of Iraqi-Americans, including U.S.citizens who voted for President Bush and Iraqi-born Muslims who oncesupported President Saddam Hussein, say that they hope to put politics asideand spark a nationwide movement to pressure both leaders to stop the war for24 hours to determine the need for humanitarian assistance.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Los Angeles Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Los Angeles  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910121  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  14A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  198  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday January 21, 199100021158,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>